description:
In generate_eui64() at lines 267-314:
```c
uint8_t hash_input[EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX_LEN + sizeof(hwid)];

hwid_len = hwinfo_get_device_id(hwid, sizeof(hwid));
// ... validation ...

memcpy(hash_input, EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX, EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX_LEN);
memcpy(hash_input + EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX_LEN, hwid, (size_t)hwid_len);
ret = lichen_sha256(hash_input, EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX_LEN + (size_t)hwid_len, hash);
```

hash_input is sized for EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX_LEN + sizeof(hwid) = 15 + 32 = 47 bytes.

But only EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX_LEN + hwid_len bytes are initialized. If hwid_len < sizeof(hwid), the remaining bytes in hash_input are uninitialized.

The SHA-256 hash is computed over exactly (EUI64_DOMAIN_PREFIX_LEN + hwid_len) bytes, so the uninitialized bytes are never read by lichen_sha256().

Additionally, secure_zero(hash_input, sizeof(hash_input)) at line 355 clears the entire buffer, including uninitialized bytes. This is fine - clearing uninitialized data is harmless.

NO BUG - the hash only reads initialized data.
